":"1351","1260":"1260","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1347":"1347","1300":"1300","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1365":"1365","1299":"1299","1298":"1298","about 1299":"about 1299","about 1310":"about 1310","about 1300":"about 1300","about 1333":"about 1333","about 1297":"about 1297","Puddington, Cheshire, England":"Puddington, Cheshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Poddington, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Rostherne, Cheshire, England":"Rostherne, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Massey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Massy</i>, a pet form of   Matthew  . Compare   Mace  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from one or more of several places in Normandy, such as Macey (Manche), Massy (Seine-Maritime), Macé-sur-Orne (Orne), and La Ferté Macé (Orne).","English: variant of <b>Marsay</b> (see   Marcey  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Mace","meanings":["A female name derived from Mace, one of the Old French forms of Mathew."]},{"name":"Massie","meanings":["pet form derived from <i>Mairead</i>, the Gaelic form of   Margaret  , with the Scottish and northern English diminutive suffix <i>-ie</i>. The name is now widely used both in Scotland and beyond as an independent given name."]},{"name":"Marsee","meanings":["English: altered form of   Massey  ."]},{"name":"Massee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Germain.","Possibly an altered form of English   Massey  .","French (<b>Massée</b>): from the feminine form of <b>Massé</b> (see   Masse  ). This surname is rare in France."]},{"name":"Massa","meanings":["pet form of both   Astrid   and   Sara ."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."]},{"name":"Macey","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a Norman baronial name from any of the places in northern France called <i>Massey</i> (Latin <i>Macciacum</i>, a derivative of the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Maccius</i>). Use as a first name has been influenced by the rhyming <i>Stacey</i>, <i>Tracy</i>, <i>Lacey</i>, and <i>Pacey</i>."]},{"name":"Masey","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Casey ."]},{"name":"Macy","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a Norman baronial name from any of the places in northern France called <i>Massey</i> (Latin <i>Macciacum</i>, a derivative of the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Maccius</i>). Use as a first name has been influenced by the rhyming <i>Stacey</i>, <i>Tracy</i>, <i>Lacey</i>, and <i>Pacey</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Massey De Pontington was born about 1297, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Hamon de Massey VII, was 38 and his mother, Katherine de Vernon, was 3. He had at least 4 sons with Valentine de Rixton. He died in 1347, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1297–1347":"umbes 1297–1347","1297–1347":"1297–1347","1298–1370":"1298–1370","1299–1365":"1299–1365","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1333–1380":"1333–1380","1260–1351":"1260–1351","1296–1300":"1296–1300","1297":"1297","1296":"1296","1351":"1351","1260":"1260","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1347":"1347","1300":"1300","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1365":"1365","1299":"1299","1298":"1298","about 1299":"umbes 1299","about 1310":"umbes 1310","about 1300":"umbes 1300","about 1333":"umbes 1333","about 1297":"umbes 1297","Puddington, Cheshire, England":"Puddington, Cheshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Poddington, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rostherne, Cheshire, England":"Rostherne, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1297–1347":"noin 1297–1347","1297–1347":"1297–1347","1298–1370":"1298–1370","1299–1365":"1299–1365","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1333–1380":"1333–1380","1260–1351":"1260–1351","1296–1300":"1296–1300","1297":"1297","1296":"1296","1351":"1351","1260":"1260","1370":"1370"